\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Handling Neumann boundary conditions in WLSQM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Example: The heat equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the general initial boundary value problem (IBVP) of the heat equation,
 with both Dirichlet and Neumann boundary conditions, and an initial condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial u}{\partial t} & =c\nabla\cdot\nabla u\quad\text{in }\Omega\times[0,t_{\mathrm{f}}]\;,\label{eq:PDE}\\
u & =u_{D}\quad\text{on }\Gamma_{D}\times[0,t_{\mathrm{f}}]\;,\label{eq:BC-Dirichlet}\\
\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla u & =q_{N}\quad\text{on }\Gamma_{N}\times[0,t_{\mathrm{f}}]\;,\label{eq:BC-Neumann}\\
u & =u_{0}\quad\text{on }\Omega\times\{t=0\}\;,\label{eq:IC}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subset\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{D}\subset\partial\Omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{N}\subset\partial\Omega$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{D}\cap\Gamma_{N}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When solving this problem with WLSQM, the main technical issue is implementing
 the Neumann boundary conditions.
 The initial condition and the Dirichlet boundary conditions are trivial;
 one can simply set the function values at the nodes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this document, we assume that we can easily obtain a pseudonormal (in
 the computer graphics sense) for each Neumann boundary point in the discretizat
ion.
 The main issue of interest is then how to insert the information from equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:BC-Neumann"

\end_inset

 into the discretization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now the standard 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 coordinate system, and a local tangential–normal coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 rotated counterclockwise in the 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

 plane by an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 (with the normal direction taken to coincide with the local outer normal
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{N}$
\end_inset

).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c:=\cos\theta\;,\quad s:=\sin\theta\;.\label{eq:c-and-s}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We can express the unit vectors of the rotated system in terms of the unit
 vectors of the standard system by (
\series bold
###TODO: add picture
\series default
)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}} & =c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;,\label{eq:tau}\\
\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}} & =-s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;.\label{eq:n}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Let us invert 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:tau"

\end_inset

–
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:n"

\end_inset

.
 Multiplying the first equation by 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and the second by 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
c\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}} & =c^{2}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+cs\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;,\\
s\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}} & =-s^{2}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+cs\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Subtracting these, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}=c\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}-s\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\;.\label{eq:ex}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Similarly, multiplying the first equation by 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and the second by 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}} & =cs\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s^{2}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;,\\
c\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}} & =-cs\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+c^{2}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}=s\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+c\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\;.\label{eq:ey}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 be a scalar field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q}:=\nabla u$
\end_inset

 its gradient.
 The gradient itself is invariant with respect to rotations, but its component
 representations are not.
 We can express the gradient in either coordinate system, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{q}=q_{\tau}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+q_{n}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}=q_{x}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+q_{y}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;.\label{eq:q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In WLSQM, when handling Neumann boundary conditions for arbitrarily oriented
 boundaries, we would like to work in the 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

 coordinate system, because this would save us the trouble of rotating the
 coordinate system locally at each boundary point in the discretization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coordinate transformations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:tau"

\end_inset

–
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:n"

\end_inset

 allow us to write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{q} & =q_{\tau}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+q_{n}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\nonumber \\
 & =q_{\tau}(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})+q_{n}(-s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})\nonumber \\
 & =(cq_{\tau}-sq_{n})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+(sq_{\tau}+cq_{n})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;,\label{eq:temp}
\end{align}

\end_inset

whence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{x}=cq_{\tau}-sq_{n}\;,\quad q_{y}=sq_{\tau}+cq_{n}\;.\label{eq:qx-and-qy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Alternatively, the inverse transformation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ex"

\end_inset

–
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ey"

\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{q} & =q_{x}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+q_{y}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\nonumber \\
 & =q_{x}(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}-s\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}})+q_{y}(s\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+c\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}})\nonumber \\
 & =(cq_{x}+sq_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+(-sq_{x}+cq_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\;,\label{eq:temp2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

whence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{\tau}=cq_{x}+sq_{y}\;,\quad q_{n}=-sq_{x}+cq_{y}\;.\label{eq:qt-and-qn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the general case, if we use 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:qt-and-qn"

\end_inset

 on the second line of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:temp"

\end_inset

, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{q} & =q_{\tau}(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})+q_{n}(-s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})\nonumber \\
 & =(cq_{x}+sq_{y})(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})+(-sq_{x}+cq_{y})(-s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})\nonumber \\
 & =(c^{2}q_{x}+csq_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+(csq_{x}+s^{2}q_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}+(s^{2}q_{x}-csq_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+(-csq_{x}+c^{2}q_{Y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\nonumber \\
 & =(c^{2}+s^{2})q_{x}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+(s^{2}+c^{2})q_{y}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\nonumber \\
 & =q_{x}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+q_{y}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;,\label{eq:temp3}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which only tells us that the transformations are correct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A typical Neumann boundary condition is the zero normal gradient condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla u)\vert_{\Gamma_{N}}=(\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\boldsymbol{q})\vert_{\Gamma_{N}}=0\;.\label{eq:zero-normal-BC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

On the other hand, in terms of the (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,n$
\end_inset

) component representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:q"

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\boldsymbol{q}=\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot(q_{\tau}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+q_{n}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}})=q_{n}\;.\label{eq:wehave}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:zero-normal-BC"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:wehave"

\end_inset

, on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{N}$
\end_inset

 it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Using this on the second line of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:temp"

\end_inset

, we have only the first term on the first line of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:temp3"

\end_inset

, obtaining
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{q}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}} & =q_{\tau}(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})\nonumber \\
 & =(cq_{x}+sq_{y})(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})\nonumber \\
 & =(c^{2}q_{x}+csq_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+(csq_{x}+s^{2}q_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;.\label{eq:q-at-Neumann-boundary}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Now because 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}=0$
\end_inset

, the extra terms do not cancel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q}=\nabla u$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{x}=\partial u/\partial x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{y}=\partial u/\partial y$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:q-at-Neumann-boundary"

\end_inset

, we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
(\nabla\cdot\nabla u)\vert_{\Gamma_{N}} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(c^{2}q_{x}+csq_{y})+\frac{\partial}{\partial y}(csq_{x}+s^{2}q_{y})\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(c^{2}\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}+cs\frac{\partial u}{\partial y})+\frac{\partial}{\partial y}(cs\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}+s^{2}\frac{\partial u}{\partial y})\nonumber \\
 & =c^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}+2cs\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x\partial y}+s^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial y^{2}}\;.\label{eq:final-result}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:final-result"

\end_inset

 lets us evaluate — directly in the original 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 coordinate system — the right-hand side of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PDE"

\end_inset

 at the Neumann boundary points of the discretization, with the boundary
 condition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:zero-normal-BC"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

baked in
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(This is similar in spirit to how Neumann boundary conditions are handled
 in the finite element method; the PDE itself is enforced also for the Neumann
 boundary degrees of freedom, with additional data from the boundary condition
 inserted.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that physically, timestepping 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PDE"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:final-result"

\end_inset

 inserted into the RHS will smooth out curvature only in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 direction (because 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:q-at-Neumann-boundary"

\end_inset

 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q}=\nabla u$
\end_inset

 to be aligned with 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

), ignoring any curvature near the boundary along the 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}$
\end_inset

 direction — which is exactly how a temperature field should behave at a
 Neumann (heat-insulating) boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For nonzero prescribed 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}=q_{N}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{q}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}} & =q_{\tau}(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})+q_{n}(-s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})\nonumber \\
 & =(cq_{x}+sq_{y})(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})+q_{N}(-s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})\nonumber \\
 & =(c^{2}q_{x}+csq_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+(csq_{x}+s^{2}q_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}+q_{N}(-s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})\nonumber \\
 & =\left(c^{2}q_{x}+csq_{y}-sq_{N}\right)\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+\left(csq_{x}+s^{2}q_{y}+cq_{N}\right)\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;.\label{eq:nonzero-Neumann}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Again, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q}=\nabla u$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{x}=\partial u/\partial x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{y}=\partial u/\partial y$
\end_inset

, so we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
(\nabla\cdot\nabla u)\vert_{\Gamma_{N}} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(c^{2}q_{x}+csq_{y}-sq_{N})+\frac{\partial}{\partial y}(csq_{x}+s^{2}q_{y}+cq_{N})\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(c^{2}\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}+cs\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}-sq_{N})+\frac{\partial}{\partial y}(cs\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}+s^{2}\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}+cq_{N})\nonumber \\
 & =c^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}+2cs\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x\partial y}+s^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial y^{2}}+\left(-s\frac{\partial}{\partial x}+c\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right)q_{N}\nonumber \\
 & =c^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}+2cs\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x\partial y}+s^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial y^{2}}+\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla q_{N}\;.\label{eq:final-result-2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

If we have a prescribed value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla q_{N}$
\end_inset

, we can enforce it using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:final-result-2"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Application to Euler flow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar tricks can be used to treat boundary conditions in other IBVPs.
 For Euler flow, the 
\emph on
no-penetration
\emph default
 boundary condition is similar to the Neumann condition of the heat equation
 in that the normal component of a quantity is known (zero!), but the tangential
 component remains free (to be computed from the PDE).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Euler flow, instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q}$
\end_inset

, we have the vector-valued velocity field 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\boldsymbol{u}=0\;.
\]

\end_inset

Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{u}=u_{\tau}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+u_{n}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}=u_{x}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+u_{y}\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;.
\]

\end_inset

By the above coordinate transformation considerations, we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{u}=u_{\tau}(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})+u_{n}(-s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})\;.
\]

\end_inset

Again, similarly to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:q-at-Neumann-boundary"

\end_inset

, at the no-penetration boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{N}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{u}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}} & =u_{\tau}(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})\\
 & =(cu_{x}+su_{y})(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y})\\
 & =(c^{2}u_{x}+csu_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+(csu_{x}+s^{2}u_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\;.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{y}$
\end_inset

 are unknowns, to be updated based on the PDE.
 The additional condition that connects 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{y}$
\end_inset

, representing 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}=0$
\end_inset

, is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:qt-and-qn"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-su_{x}+cu_{y}=0\;.\label{eq:normal-velocity-zero}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

