\begin_layout Subsection
Euler flow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compressible flow.
 Time evolution equations for fluid density and flow velocity, in an Eulerian
 frame, in index notation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
(\partial_{t}+u_{j}\partial_{j})\rho & =-\rho\partial_{j}u_{j}\label{eq:rho-index}\\
(\partial_{t}+u_{j}\partial_{j})u_{i} & =-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\partial_{i}\rho+g_{i}\label{eq:u-index}
\end{align}

\end_inset

We may also write this in direct notation: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla\right)\rho & =-\rho\nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{u}\label{eq:rho-direct}\\
\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla\right)\boldsymbol{u} & =-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\nabla\rho+\boldsymbol{g}\label{eq:u-direct}
\end{align}

\end_inset

To keep WLSQM fast (to avoid the need to re-generate neighborhoods with
 upwinding), we use operator splitting (second-order symmetrized Strang)
 to separate the transport into a subproblem that can be handled by a specialize
d algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that in the splitting, each subproblem gets its own copy of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial t$
\end_inset

 term; one cannot simply sum the subproblems to get the original problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subproblems for fluid density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t} & =-\rho\nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{u}\label{eq:rhosource}\\
\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla\right)\rho & =0\label{eq:rho-advect}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Subproblems for (Eulerian) flow velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}}{\partial t} & =-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\nabla\rho+\boldsymbol{g}\label{eq:u-pressure}\\
\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla\right)\boldsymbol{u} & =0\label{eq:u-advect}
\end{align}

\end_inset

For both 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

, the second subproblem is pure advection at velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using an explicit time integrator, integrating from 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}+\Delta t$
\end_inset

, we interpret this as advection by the old (last known) 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}(t_{0})=:\boldsymbol{u}_{0}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{u}_{0}\cdot\nabla\right)\rho=0\;,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{u}_{0}\cdot\nabla\right)\boldsymbol{u}=0\;.
\]

\end_inset

Thus over each timestep, we have a linear hyperbolic first-order transport
 problem.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The advection subproblem for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-advect"

\end_inset

, is fully decoupled; the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

 transports itself, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 having no effect.
 In the advection problem for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rho-advect"

\end_inset

, there is one-way coupling; the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

 transports the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other two subproblems, equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rhosource"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-pressure"

\end_inset

, are bidirectionally coupled in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho,\boldsymbol{u})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The advection subproblems require inflow BCs.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the coupled system, the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

 suggests we need to prescribe 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}$
\end_inset

 at the boundaries.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rhosource"

\end_inset

 accounts for changes in density caused by sources and sinks in the flow
 velocity field, while equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-pressure"

\end_inset

 accounts for local acceleration due to body forces (such as gravity) and
 the pressure response.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\rho)\nabla\rho\equiv\nabla(\ln\rho)$
\end_inset

, but the left-hand side is more convenient for the solver.
 Note also that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is large (for air, on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{5}$
\end_inset

); the pressure response of the velocity field is thus very fast when compared
 to the advection.
 (Physically: compare typical flow velocities with the speed of sound.) Thus,
 this is a stiff problem, where the pressure response term limits the maximum
 possible timestep size.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This suggests that we may internally use a smaller timestep for the stiff
 coupled subproblems, and then use a single large timestep for the advection
 subproblems (for numerical stability, pure advection only needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{CFL}<1$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The stiff coupled part requires solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\rho$
\end_inset

 at each small timestep (via WLSQM), but global model interpolation is only
 needed by the advection part.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the viewpoint of information flow, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rhosource"

\end_inset

 has no preferred direction in space, so symmetric (central) neighborhoods
 in WLSQM are expected work well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Likewise, there should be no preferred direction of information flow in
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-pressure"

\end_inset

, so symmetric neighborhoods (taking the gradient centrally) should work
 also there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Only in the advection subproblems 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rho-advect"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-advect"

\end_inset

, the differential operator has a preferred direction, along streamlines.
 Moreover, the combination 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial t+\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla$
\end_inset

 makes this preferred direction 
\emph on
asymmetric in time
\emph default
.
 In physical terms, this operator the transport of a field, by a velocity
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, when updating an Eulerian description of the target field 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial t+\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla$
\end_inset

 operates on, one should only look at information that is 
\emph on
yet to arrive
\emph default
 to the point under consideration; information that has 
\emph on
already passed
\emph default
 the point should have no effect on the update.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for Euler flows, 
\emph on
a priori
