 The kinematically forced inflow at the boundary will cause 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{u}<0$
\end_inset

 in the first inside-domain layer of nodes (because 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial u_{x}/\partial x<0$
\end_inset

), causing 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\rho/\partial t>0$
\end_inset

 there.
 Then, at the next timestep, in the third layer of nodes (on the other side
 of the density peak) 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\rho/\partial x<0$
\end_inset

, whence 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{x}>0$
\end_inset

.
 This should cause a compressive pressure wave to propagate across the domain,
 causing the flow velocity to become nonzero, thus starting up the advection.
 Try this first.
\end_layout

