\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
First, note that in a steady-state (
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\boldsymbol{u}/\partial t\equiv0$
\end_inset

) incompressible flow in the absence of body forces, velocity along each
 streamline is constant (Bernoulli's principle, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernoulli%27s_principle"

\end_inset

 ), 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla)\boldsymbol{u}\equiv0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A steady state for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 obviously exists.
 From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rho-direct"

\end_inset

, taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\rho/\partial t\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla\rho=-\rho\nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{u}\;.
\]

\end_inset

Alternatively, we may write this as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\left(\frac{1}{\rho}\nabla\rho\right)=-\nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{u}\;,
\]

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla)(\ln\rho)=-\nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{u}\;.
\]

\end_inset

In the absence of body forces, potential flow is divergence-free, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{u}\equiv0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla)(\ln\rho)=0$
\end_inset

.
 In this situation, 
\emph on
density remains constant along streamlines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-direct"

\end_inset

, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\boldsymbol{u}/\partial t\equiv0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla)\boldsymbol{u}\equiv0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\boldsymbol{g}-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\nabla\rho\;,
\]

\end_inset

whence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{\alpha}\boldsymbol{g}=\frac{1}{\rho}\nabla\rho=\nabla(\ln\rho)\;.
\]

\end_inset

We thus obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla(\ln\rho)$
\end_inset

 algebraically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}\equiv0$
\end_inset

, we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\rho=\mathrm{const.}$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\mathrm{const.}$
\end_inset

 as the corresponding density IC, as is indeed expected for incompressible
 flow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}\not\equiv0$
\end_inset

, let us assume that the gravitational field 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}$
\end_inset

 is uniform.
 We can start from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

downmost
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 point in the domain, set a value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 there, and then linearly increase 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\rho$
\end_inset

 moving 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upward
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the gravitational field.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Doing this accounts for hydrostatic pressure.
 Maybe not necessary to include nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}$
\end_inset

 in our application?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is not completely rigorous; taking 
\begin_inset Formula $(\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla)\boldsymbol{u}\equiv0$
\end_inset

 we have already assumed the absence of body forces.
 Thus this is an ad hoc approximation, applicable when the body forces are
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
