\begin_layout Itemize
Summary: for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}\equiv0$
\end_inset

, the IC for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\mathrm{const.}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
BCs: physics dictates 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot(\boldsymbol{u}-\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}})\equiv0$
\end_inset

 (for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) at obstacles.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For simplicity, let us first consider stationary obstacles, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}}\equiv0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}$
\end_inset

 constant in time.
 Consider the coupled subproblems.
 Let us start with the pressure subproblem for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-pressure"

\end_inset

, written at the obstacle boundary:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}}{\partial t}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}}=\boldsymbol{g}-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\nabla\rho\;.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}\equiv0$
\end_inset

 along the whole boundary, also 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\tau}u_{n}\equiv0$
\end_inset

, and we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial t}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}} & =g_{\tau}-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\nabla\rho\;,\\
0=\frac{\partial u_{n}}{\partial t}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}} & =g_{n}-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho\;.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The first equation gives an update formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 at the boundary, whereas the second gives (a trivial update for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}$
\end_inset

 and) a constraint that must be satisfied by 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}\equiv0$
\end_inset

, the constraint simplifies into
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho)\vert_{\Gamma_{N}}=0\;.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
All these relations hold at the beginning of the timestep, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In practice, to mitigate discretization error (especially at curved boundaries),
 on input it is preferable to use a trick: take 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}=\mathrm{sgn}(\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\boldsymbol{u})\left|\boldsymbol{u}\right|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 (instead of applying coordinate system conversion to the actual 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{x},u_{y})$
\end_inset

 representation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

 at the boundaries is stored in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 coordinates, this input conversion is equivalent to a do-nothing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On output, use the updated 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}^{*}$
\end_inset

, and set 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}^{*}=0$
\end_inset

, before applying conversion to 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 coordinates (now using the coordinate conversion formulas).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When updating 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

, we evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\nabla\rho$
\end_inset

 by WLSQM.
 At the boundary, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\nabla\rho$
\end_inset

 is conveniently available in the local 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To prescribe 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\rho/\partial n=0$
\end_inset

, use local 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 coordinates for the boundary nodes (also for the density field), which
 allows setting 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\partial\rho/\partial y=0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the solver.
 WLSQM then outputs the appropriate value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 that makes the field satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\rho/\partial n=0$
\end_inset

 at the boundary.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
alternative, bad idea: Approximate by copying the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 from slightly inside the domain (in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}$
\end_inset

), making the normal derivative approximately zero...
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Just to be sure, consider also the source/sink subproblem for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 at the obstacle boundary:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}}=-\rho\nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{u}=-\rho(\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial\tau}+\frac{\partial u_{n}}{\partial n})
\]

\end_inset

The (physically appropriate) BCs tell us nothing about the components of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

; thus this equation produces no new constraints.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This also holds in the case of moving obstacles.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Summary: for the coupled subproblems, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}\equiv0$
\end_inset

, the obstacle boundary conditions 
\series bold
for stationary obstacles
\series default
 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial t}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}}=-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\nabla\rho\;,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{n}=0\;,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho)\vert_{\Gamma_{N}}=0\;.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In fact, if the second and third equation are applied first, the first equation
 is then just the PDE itself (the coupled subproblem for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-pressure"

\end_inset

), written at the obstacle boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The second equation is the original BC for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The third equation is a consequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}=\text{\mathrm{const.}}$
\end_inset

 (whence 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial u_{n}/\partial t=0$
\end_inset

) and the PDE 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-pressure"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the solver, at the boundary, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\nabla\rho$
\end_inset

 is conveniently available in the local 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 representation.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Conversion of vectors from 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 components to 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 components.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Once we have the new tangential velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}^{*}$
\end_inset

, in order to obtain the new 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{x}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{y}^{*}$
\end_inset

, we have the linear equation system
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
cu_{x}^{*}+su_{y}^{*} & =u_{\tau}^{*}\;,\\
-su_{x}^{*}+cu_{y}^{*} & =u_{n}^{*}\;,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}^{*}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In matrix form,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{A}\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{b}\;,
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{A}=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
c & s\\
-s & c
\end{array}\right]\;,\quad\boldsymbol{x}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
u_{x}^{*}\\
u_{y}^{*}
\end{array}\right]\;,\quad\boldsymbol{b}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
u_{\tau}^{*}\\
u_{n}^{*}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Taking note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 represents a rotation, it is orthogonal, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}^{-1}=\boldsymbol{A}^{\mathrm{T}}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{A}^{\mathrm{T}}\boldsymbol{A}=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
c & -s\\
s & c
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{rr}
c & s\\
-s & c
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
c^{2}+s^{2} & cs-sc\\
sc-cs & s^{2}+c^{2}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\;,
\]

\end_inset

so in general,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
u_{x}^{*}\\
u_{y}^{*}
\end{array}\right]=\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{A}^{-1}\boldsymbol{b}=\boldsymbol{A}^{\mathrm{T}}\boldsymbol{b}=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
c & -s\\
s & c
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
u_{\tau}^{*}\\
u_{n}^{*}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Thus, explicitly for the velocity,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{x}^{*}=cu_{\tau}^{*}\;,\quad u_{y}^{*}=su_{\tau}^{*}\;,
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}^{*}=0$
\end_inset

 by the boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\boldsymbol{u}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider now 
\series bold
moving obstacles
\series default
.
 (Rotation, translation and deformation are allowed.) The local time derivative
 of the flow velocity field in arbitrary orthonormal (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,n$
\end_inset

) coordinates, in the case where the coordinate system is allowed to rotate,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\theta(t)$
\end_inset

, becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}}{\partial t} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial t}(u_{\tau}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+u_{n}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}})\\
 & =\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial t}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+u_{\tau}\frac{\partial\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial u_{n}}{\partial t}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}+u_{n}\frac{\partial\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}}{\partial t}\\
 & =\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial t}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+u_{\tau}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left[\begin{array}{r}
\cos\theta\\
\sin\theta
\end{array}\right]+\frac{\partial u_{n}}{\partial t}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}+u_{n}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left[\begin{array}{r}
-\sin\theta\\
\cos\theta
\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial t}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+u_{\tau}\left[\begin{array}{r}
-\sin\theta\\
\cos\theta
\end{array}\right]\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial u_{n}}{\partial t}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}+u_{n}\left[\begin{array}{r}
-\cos\theta\\
-\sin\theta
\end{array}\right]\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}\\
 & =\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial t}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+u_{\tau}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial u_{n}}{\partial t}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}+u_{n}(-\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}})\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}\\
 & =\left(\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial t}+u_{n}\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}\right)\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+\left(\frac{\partial u_{n}}{\partial t}-u_{\tau}\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}\right)\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\;.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\theta/\partial t$
\end_inset

 is considered known.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}\equiv0$
\end_inset

, we obtain the tangential and normal components of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-pressure"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial t}+u_{n}\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t} & =-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\nabla\rho\;,\\
\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial u_{n}}{\partial t}-u_{\tau}\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t} & =-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho\;.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Accounting for the fact that at the boundary, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot(\boldsymbol{u}-\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}})\equiv0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}=u_{n,\mathrm{obst}}$
\end_inset

 (known!), and rearranging terms, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial t} & =-u_{n,\mathrm{obst}}\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\nabla\rho\;,\\
\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho & =\frac{\rho}{\alpha}\left(u_{\tau}\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}-\frac{\partial u_{n,\mathrm{obst}}}{\partial t}\right)\;.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This accounts for both normal-direction acceleration and rotation of the
 obstacle.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This reduces correctly.
 If the obstacle does not move (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 constant in time (but still local to each point on the surface!), 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n,\mathrm{obst}}\equiv0$
\end_inset

), we again have 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho=0$
\end_inset

.
 Note also 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}=u_{n,\mathrm{obst}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The first equation reduces to the previous PDE for the tangential velocity
 component 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The LHS will be obtained for the same point of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 from which data is fed to the RHS.
 If we use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 data at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}$
\end_inset

 refer to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,n$
\end_inset

) coordinate system at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The result is also expressed in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 system.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For FSI problems, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\theta/\partial t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n,\mathrm{obst}}$
\end_inset

 may be challenging to obtain for 
\begin_inset Formula $t>t_{0}$
\end_inset

 before the timestep is complete (these are needed for RK2 integration of
 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

).
 Must model somehow.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Fixed point iteration possible (IG = use the values at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

), but very slow, since it must iterate between fluid and structure solvers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Trivial model (values from the structural model remain constant across the
 timestep) also possible.
 Fast, but not very accurate.
 Maybe good enough?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Structure solver must in any case provide not only 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}}$
\end_inset

 (velocity, not displacement!) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, but also 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\theta/\partial t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}}/\partial t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the structural discretization uses a first-order form with displacement
 and velocity DOFs, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\theta/\partial t$
\end_inset

 are easy to obtain.
 The acceleration can be computed for each structural DOF from the first-order
 ODE system (to get it as accurately as possible).
 The result can be converted to obstacle acceleration in a format that the
 fluid solver understands.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If we want to have 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho$
\end_inset

 at the end of the timestep, we can (after applying the explicit time integratio
n) just re-evaluate the RHS of the above expression, using the new 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\vert_{t=t_{0}+\Delta t}$
\end_inset

 instead of the old 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\vert_{t=t_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Obviously, then 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}+\Delta t$
\end_inset

 also in all terms on the RHS (use the updated solution fields!).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho$
\end_inset

 at the beginning of the next timestep, so we need to compute it anyway.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

, provided that the rotation increment 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\theta$
\end_inset

 during the timestep is small, we can use the 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}=\mathrm{sgn}(\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\boldsymbol{u})\left|\boldsymbol{u}\right|$
\end_inset

 trick (i.e.
 just rotate the flow vector, keeping it tangential, now with the updated
 surface).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Doesn't matter whether we use 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\vert_{t=t_{0}+\Delta t}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\vert_{t=t_{0}}$
\end_inset

, since we only take 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{sgn(\dots)}$
\end_inset

, and the rotation is small.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In practice, we may performance-optimize further.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

 at the boundary is stored in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 coordinates, this is equivalent to a do-nothing!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We simply re-interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{\tau},u_{n})$
\end_inset

 as if it was already expressed in the updated 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 coordinates; this effectively rotates the vector into the new 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 coordinates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Only if the 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

 is needed at the end of the timestep, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}+\Delta t$
\end_inset

, we must use 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\vert_{t=t_{0}+\Delta t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\vert_{t=t_{0}+\Delta t}$
\end_inset

 in the coordinate system conversion.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Some obstacles may remain stationary (no advection with flow) but undergo
 small vibrations (in response to the flow or otherwise) around a reference
 configuration.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Each surface segment oscillates around its local reference position and
 orientation.
 In this case we can probably get away with not actually updating the point
 clouds into the new 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 system at each timestep, since the distances and directions are always
 close to those in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

local reference (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,n$
\end_inset

) system
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (computed for the reference configuration).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This gives major savings in computation time, because the boundary point
 clouds can be preprocessed just like for classical rigid stationary obstacles.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This makes the fluid solver just as fast as for the rigid obstacle case.
 Useful for realtime applications in FSI of structures undergoing small
 vibrations?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the fluid model, the obstacle then remains geometrically stationary,
 but its vibration is seen by the no-penetration boundary conditions, thereby
 affecting the flow.
 This is an adaptation (for Euler flows) of the approach that was used for
 potential flows in our earlier studies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This can be used in the papermaking application having small transverse
 deflections.
 The axial motion of the paper web is not seen by the Euler flow surrounding
 it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Even for a Navier–Stokes flow, in this application the structural geometry
 remains stationary in the Eulerian frame, and only the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

zero relative velocity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 BC is affected (since the obstacle surface moves axially).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Could test this with a simpler problem, e.g.
 a kinematically oscillating rigid cylinder.
 This gives a one-way coupling, with a trivial structural model driving
 the fluid model.
 (With applications to 2D musical instruments and/or spatial audio processing?
 Record the numerical pressure response at some point(s) in the domain.
 Probably too expensive computationally, though; Helmholtz is much cheaper
 than an Euler flow.)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For compressible Navier–Stokes, doing this is even easier: then at the obstacle
 surface, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}-\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}}\equiv0$
\end_inset

; this fixes both components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Add the 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\nabla\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

 diffusion term to the subproblem that was used to derive the boundary condition
s.
 Obtain a condition for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Something like:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}}{\partial t}=-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\nabla\rho+\nu\nabla\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{u}\;,
\]

\end_inset

whence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}}}{\partial t}=-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\nabla\rho+\nu\nabla\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}}\;,
\]

\end_inset

and by rearranging,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla\rho=\frac{\rho}{\alpha}\left(\nu\nabla\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}}-\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}}}{\partial t}\right)\;.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}}$
\end_inset

 is not a rigid-body motion, since the obstacle will deform while vibrating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To evaluate the laplacian, it may be convenient to use 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 coordinates, because then the axis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}$
\end_inset

 are constant in space.
 The result can then be rotated into the local 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 coordinates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}}/\partial t$
\end_inset

 term can be expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 coordinates as before.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Inflow boundaries.
 Here we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}=\boldsymbol{u}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

, whence 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\boldsymbol{u}/\partial t=\partial\boldsymbol{u}_{\infty}/\partial t=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}}{\partial t}=\boldsymbol{g}-\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\nabla\rho\;,
\]

\end_inset

from which (if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}\equiv0$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla\rho=0\;.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No-inflow free-stream boundaries (top, bottom, right): maybe we can just
 ignore these?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Use the PDE to update the solution as if the node was inside the domain.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider now the advection subproblems.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Itemize
For a stationary obstacle, from the first subproblem for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-pressure"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\equiv\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\boldsymbol{u}\right)=\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}}{\partial t}=\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{g}-\alpha\frac{1}{\rho}\nabla\rho\right)
\]

\end_inset

Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho=\frac{\rho}{\alpha}\,\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\boldsymbol{g}\;,
\]

\end_inset

which gives an additional BC for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 For a moving obstacle, this becomes a bit more complicated:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0\equiv\frac{\partial}{\partial t}(\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\boldsymbol{u}) & =\frac{\partial\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}}{\partial t}\cdot\boldsymbol{u}+\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}}{\partial t}\\
 & =\beta\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\boldsymbol{u}+\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}}{\partial t}\\
 & =\beta\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\boldsymbol{u}+\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{g}-\alpha\frac{1}{\rho}\nabla\rho\right)\;,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 depends on the rate of rotation of the obstacle surface.
 This seems a complicated way to do it...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Alternative try: 
\end_layout

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rho-advect"

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t}=-\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla\rho=-(u_{\tau}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+u_{n}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}})\cdot\nabla\rho\;,
\]

\end_inset

but because 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\boldsymbol{u}=u_{n}\equiv0$
\end_inset

 at the obstacle boundary, the second term vanishes, leaving only
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}} & =-u_{\tau}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\nabla\rho\\
 & =-(cu_{x}+su_{y})\left(c\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+s\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\right)\cdot\nabla\rho\\
 & =-\left[(c^{2}u_{x}+csu_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{x}+(csu_{x}+s^{2}u_{y})\widehat{\boldsymbol{e}}_{y}\right]\cdot\nabla\rho\\
 & =-\left[(c^{2}u_{x}+csu_{y})\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial x}+(csu_{x}+s^{2}u_{y})\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial y}\right]\;.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We have obtained a separate update formula for the boundary nodes.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
But we don't need it — we already have the BC update above.
 (See algorithm below.)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
On the other hand, the first line says this is 1D advection of the field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, along the local tangent direction of the boundary:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t}+u_{\tau}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\nabla\rho=0\;.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus it is equivalent to treat it as such in the semi-Lagrangean advection
 procedure.
 Compute 2D advection inside the domain; compute 1D advection along the
 boundary at the obstacle boundaries.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A small error will be introduced due to discretization, especially at curved
 boundaries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How to prevent the discretization error from corrupting 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

 in the pressure subproblem?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
It may be enough that the pressure subproblem corrects for it by imposing
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho=0$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
We may simply impose that already here
\series default
, considering that the next update for the coupled subproblem (stiff subproblem)
 would do it anyway.
 If the result is always overwritten, it makes no sense to bother advecting
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 along the boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can do the same for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

.
 Enforce the boundary conditions already here; the advection along the boundary
 does not matter, because the next update of the coupled subproblem overwrites
 it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus the complete 
\series bold
solver algorithm
\series default
 for one timestep becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
1) advect (for large timestep), ignore BCs except at inflow boundaries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
2) reset time counter (how much of the large timestep processed) for the
 stiff part 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
3) update boundary nodes (using BCs from the coupled subproblem) with the
 currently latest available data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
4) if counter says the whole large timestep has been processed, DONE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
5) update the stiff part, inside-domain nodes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
6) jump to step 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
in practice, must account for symmetric Strang splitting (the above is just
 first-order Marchuk–Yanenko).
 Process the stiff part for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t/2$
\end_inset

; then advect for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

, then again process the stiff part for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t/2$
\end_inset

.
 Snapshot the solution fields for output.
 Repeat.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
advection with MacCormack is 
\begin_inset Formula $O((\Delta t)^{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
stiff part could be integrated using RK2, also 
\begin_inset Formula $O((\Delta t)^{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
boundary nodes can easily get the old value, but how about the 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 update that gets only 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial u_{\tau}/\partial t$
\end_inset

 and needs to integrate in time? It seems we must interleave the RK2 integration
 of the inside-domain part with the boundary update?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let's do this...
 RK2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{k}_{1} & =\boldsymbol{f}(\boldsymbol{u}_{n},\,t_{n})\;,\\
\boldsymbol{k}_{2} & =\boldsymbol{f}(\boldsymbol{u}_{n}+\beta\,\Delta t\,\boldsymbol{k}_{1},\,t_{n}+\beta\,\Delta t)\;,\\
\boldsymbol{u}_{n+1} & =\boldsymbol{u}_{n}+\Delta t\left[(1-\frac{1}{2\beta})\boldsymbol{k}_{1}+\frac{1}{2\beta}\boldsymbol{k}_{2}\right]\;,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in(0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Classical choices 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/2$
\end_inset

 (explicit midpoint method), 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2/3$
\end_inset

 (Ralston's method), 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1$
\end_inset

 (Heun's method / explicit trapezoid rule).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exiting advection step, entering stiff part update.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At the beginning of a timestep, enforce boundary conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 simultaneously in the interior and on the boundaries
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This needs data only from 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We have also 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial u_{\tau}/\partial t$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Repeat for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
As input, we have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

candidate data
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}_{n}+\beta\,\Delta t\,\boldsymbol{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1$
\end_inset

, this is the forward Euler prediction)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Enforce boundary conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}+\beta\,\Delta t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 contains an approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial u_{\tau}/\partial t$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}+\beta\,\Delta t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How about FSI? Must model the behavior of the structure across the timestep
 before we actually have it...
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}_{\mathrm{obst}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 not yet available at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}+\beta\,\Delta t$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
RK2 also outputs updated 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 behaves otherwise like an inside-domain DOF, but with a different update
 formula.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
After computing the last 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 for this stiff part update, enforce boundary conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}\cdot\nabla\rho$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}+\Delta t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
May be important, because the advection step comes next
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
The stuff below here is not needed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
From the advection subproblem for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:u-advect"

\end_inset

, we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{u}}{\partial t}=-\boldsymbol{u}\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{u}=-(u_{\tau}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}+u_{n}\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}})\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{u}\;.
\]

\end_inset

To be completely unambiguous, let us use index notation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial t}=-u_{j}\partial_{j}u_{i}=-(u_{\tau}\partial_{\tau}+u_{n}\partial_{n})u_{i}\;.
\]

\end_inset

Due to BCs, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}\equiv0$
\end_inset

 at the boundary.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $i=\{\tau,n\}$
\end_inset

, this gives two update formulas in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 coordinates:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial t}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}}=-u_{\tau}\partial_{\tau}u_{\tau}
\]

\end_inset

(representing 1D advection of the tangential component along the boundary,
 as is physically expected) and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u_{n}}{\partial t}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}}=-u_{\tau}\partial_{\tau}u_{n}\;.
\]

\end_inset

But since 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}\equiv0$
\end_inset

 along the whole boundary, also 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\tau}u_{n}\equiv0$
\end_inset

 and hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u_{n}}{\partial t}\vert_{\Gamma_{N}}=0\;,
\]

\end_inset

which just confirms that the normal velocity remains at zero.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For rotating obstacles, this becomes more complicated, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\boldsymbol{n}}$
\end_inset

 no longer remain constant.
 The local 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 coordinate system rotates with the obstacle, and it becomes important to
 distinguish whether we use the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\Delta t$
\end_inset

) local coordinate system.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider 1D advection along the boundary.
 Now we don't have direct access to the tangential velocity field 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

, but we can compute it as 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}=cu_{x}+su_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the old solution fulfills the no-penetration BC, it will also hold
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $-su_{x}+cu_{y}=u_{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Thus a way to correct for small error 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}=O(\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

 arising from discretization: take the magnitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\boldsymbol{u}\right|$
\end_inset

 and use that as 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

, correcting for the sign, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{sgn}(u_{\tau})=\mathrm{sgn}(\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\boldsymbol{u})$
\end_inset

.
 Do the same when converting back.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Explicitly, take 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}=\mathrm{sgn}(\widehat{\boldsymbol{\tau}}\cdot\boldsymbol{u})\left|\boldsymbol{u}\right|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 on input (do not actually use the coordinate conversion formulas).
 On output, use the updated 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}^{*}$
\end_inset

, and set 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}^{*}=0$
\end_inset

, before applying conversion to 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 coordinates (now using the coordinate conversion formulas).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Maybe compute 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 as a field in a small neighborhood and use semi-Lagrangean advection along
 the boundary direction?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We already have fields for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{y}$
\end_inset

 that we can interpolate.
 Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 at the appropriate point using the interpolated 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Alternatively: converting the RHS partially to 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 coordinates, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial u_{\tau}}{\partial t} & =-u_{\tau}(c\frac{\partial}{\partial x}+s\frac{\partial}{\partial y})(cu_{x}+su_{y})\nonumber \\
 & =-u_{\tau}\left[c^{2}\frac{\partial u_{x}}{\partial x}+cs\left(\frac{\partial u_{y}}{\partial x}+\frac{\partial u_{x}}{\partial y}\right)+s^{2}\frac{\partial u_{y}}{\partial y}\right]\;.\label{eq:update-utau}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The parenthetical expression can be evaluated using WLSQM.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
But this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fights
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the physical direction of information flow, because in WLSQM we use symmetric
 neighborhoods to generate the derivatives.
 Thus numerical stability can be bad.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The rest is better to keep in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau,n)$
\end_inset

 coordinates.
 We have the numerical value of the old 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

.
 We then compute the time derivative of this 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 using the above equation, and perform the time integration to obtain the
 new value 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For curved obstacles, we must update this slightly, since 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 are then no longer constant in space.
 But maybe this is ok for piecewise linear obstacles with the nodes placed
 at segment midpoints (or anywhere except at a corner)?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The advection problems can be handled by the semi-Lagrangean approach with
 MacCormack correction to obtain second-order accuracy.
 Global patched surrogate model interpolation gives access to the required
 interpolated values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The clamping required for MacCormack can be achieved in a fast solver by
 using the data values from the (pre-computed) neighborhood of the node
 whose model the interpolator picked.
 (The interpolator must return this information!) This approach saves an
 (expensive) search for the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 closest nodes from the point at which the interpolant was computed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To match the accuracy, for the time integration, we choose (parametric)
 RK2.
 It has second-order accuracy, and it is computationally light, requiring
 only two stages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For the initial flowfield, we can achieve no-penetration by solving a potential
 flow problem.
 To do this using WLSQM, convert the Poisson problem (for the velocity potential
) to the time-dependent diffusion problem (heat equation) by adding the
 time-dependent term, set zero Neumann BCs at the obstacles, and integrate
 until the steady state is approximately reached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus, assume that the old solution fulfills the no-penetration BC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Fit the model.
 This enables interpolation, needed for the semi-Lagrangean approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The advection step — which strictly requires only inflow BCs — will introduce
 a small error (nonzero normal velocity component) especially near curved
 parts of the boundary (discretized into straight segments).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Can we simply re-align the velocity at the boundary nodes (turn the vector
 until it is aligned), and then re-fit only the affected neighborhoods (those
 having at least one obstacle node)?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
(Requires a per-problem-instance flag array in the solver, to switch off
 solving for instances that need no updating.)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
